    "Let me analyze the reaction to identify the roles of reagents, solvent, and catalyst.\n\nThe reaction SMILES: CN(C)C=O.COC(OC)N(C)C.Nc1nc2c(ncn2COCCO)c(=O)[nH]1>>CN(C)C=Nc1nc2c(ncn2COCCO)c(=O)[nH]1\n\nLet me parse the components:\n\n1. CN(C)C=O - This is DMF (dimethylformamide)\n2. COC(OC)N(C)C - This is dimethylformamide dimethyl acetal (DMF-DMA, or N,N-dimethylformamide dimethyl acetal)\n3. Nc1nc2c(ncn2COCCO)c(=O)[nH]1 - This is an amino-substituted purine derivative (2-amino-9-(2-hydroxyethoxymethyl)purin-6-one, which is acyclovir or similar)\n\nProduct: CN(C)C=Nc1nc2c(ncn2COCCO)c(=O)[nH]1 - The amino group has been converted to a dimethylaminomethylene (dimethylformamidine) group.\n\nLooking at the mapped reaction:\n- The NH2 group on the purine reacts with DMF-DMA (COC(OC)N(C)C) to form the dimethylaminomethylene derivative\n- DMF (CN(C)C=O) serves as the solvent\n\nThe mechanism: DMF-DMA is a formylating agent that converts primary amines to dimethylformamidines. The dimethyl acetal acts as the reagent that provides the CH=N(CH3)2 moiety. DMF serves as the solvent.\n\nSo:\n- DMF (CN(C)C=O): Solvent\n- DMF-DMA (COC(OC)N(C)C): Reagent\n- The amino-purine: Substrate/reactant\n- No catalyst is explicitly present\n\nLet me format this as a condition_role_mapping."
